docs.abstract: Several signs of economic stress may keep the Fed from raising interest rates to a full percentage point.
docs.snippet: Several signs of economic stress may keep the Fed from raising interest rates to a full percentage point.
docs.lead_paragraph: This week, the Federal Reserve will decide on its next move for interest rates. The decision, expected to be announced on Wednesday, will almost certainly be to raise its benchmark rate. The U.S. economy is facing its worst bout of inflation in four decades, and higher interest rates are likely to slow the economy and ease price increases. But how much remains a question.

headline.main: Cooling the Economy Without Crushing It

byline.original: By Andrew Ross Sorkin, Vivian Giang, Stephen Gandel, Lauren Hirsch, Ephrat Livni and Jenny Gross

docs.abstract: Sports are the lifeblood of TV but also choking it. Big Tech is following a similar playbook.
docs.snippet: Sports are the lifeblood of TV but also choking it. Big Tech is following a similar playbook.
docs.lead_paragraph: Sports and TV have thrived together. Our entertainment future will be shaped by whether streaming and sports can repeat that mostly happy partnership.

headline.main: Will Streaming Save Sports or Kill It?

docs.abstract: Some tech companies’ earnings are flagging, in what could be a positive sign for the Federal Reserve.
docs.snippet: Some tech companies’ earnings are flagging, in what could be a positive sign for the Federal Reserve.
docs.lead_paragraph: The long-booming bottom lines of major tech companies are all of a sudden smaller than expected. That might be a good thing. Big Tech sailed through the pandemic with its profits mostly intact. The fact that some firms’ results are now flagging could be a positive sign for the Federal Reserve, which is trying to engineer a slowdown as it fights the nation’s worst bout of inflation in four decades.

byline.original: By Andrew Ross Sorkin, Vivian Giang, Stephen Gandel, Lauren Hirsch, Ephrat Livni and Jenny Gross

docs.abstract: A class-action lawsuit represented customers who sought repairs for the troubled MacBook keyboard, released in certain laptops from 2015 to 2019. Many were frustrated by typing errors.
docs.snippet: A class-action lawsuit represented customers who sought repairs for the troubled MacBook keyboard, released in certain laptops from 2015 to 2019. Many were frustrated by typing errors.
docs.lead_paragraph: Apple agreed on Monday to pay a $50 million settlement on a class-action lawsuit over so-called butterfly keyboards, a component of some MacBook laptops that left many users fuming in key-smashing frustration over typing failures.

headline.main: Apple Agrees to $50 Million Settlement Over Butterfly Keyboard Complaints

docs.abstract: Tech companies are slowing their frenetic hiring, but a combination of dominance and diversity is turning out to be — yet again — an overwhelming asset.
docs.snippet: Tech companies are slowing their frenetic hiring, but a combination of dominance and diversity is turning out to be — yet again — an overwhelming asset.
docs.lead_paragraph: No boom can last forever, even for the technology industry’s most affluent companies. Investors punished the biggest tech companies earlier this year, erasing $2 trillion in market value over fears the industry would falter in the face of rising inflation and a slowing economy.

headline.main: Big Tech Is Proving Resilient as the Economy Cools
headline.print_headline: After $2 Trillion Slide, Tech Giants Swagger Their Way Through a Storm

docs.abstract: Three years after promising to work “long into the future” with the man behind its candy-colored computers, Apple and Mr. Ive are through.
docs.snippet: Three years after promising to work “long into the future” with the man behind its candy-colored computers, Apple and Mr. Ive are through.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — When Jony Ive, Apple’s influential design leader, exited the company in 2019, Tim Cook, its chief executive, reassured customers that Mr. Ive, the man who gave the world candy-colored computers, would work exclusively with the company for many years.

headline.main: Apple Ends Consulting Agreement With Jony Ive, Its Former Design Leader
headline.print_headline: Apple Breaks With Ex-Chief Of Design Unit

docs.abstract: With the metaverse looming, a shift in designer could make a big difference.
docs.snippet: With the metaverse looming, a shift in designer could make a big difference.
docs.lead_paragraph: So Jony Ive, the former Apple chief design officer and consultant, and the man most responsible for the visual allure of Apple products — the man who helped transform computers and phones into objects of desire, who made them more than mere vectors of functionality, but rather badges of identity — and his erstwhile employer have reportedly agreed to sever their last ties.

headline.main: Who Will Make Apple Fashionable Now?
headline.print_headline: Waiting for a New Reality to Drop at Apple

docs.abstract: The official was the senior director of corporate law at Apple until he was fired in late 2018.
docs.snippet: The official was the senior director of corporate law at Apple until he was fired in late 2018.
docs.lead_paragraph: A former senior lawyer at Apple who enforced its insider-trading policies pleaded guilty on Thursday to perpetrating an insider-trading scheme, which prosecutors said had involved making stock transactions before the company announced it fell short of iPhone sales expectations.

headline.main: Former Apple Lawyer Pleads Guilty to Insider Trading
